{
  "Tides are primarily caused by:": "",
  "Differences in water temperature between the equator and poles": "",
  "Wind blowing across the ocean surface": "",
  "The gravitational pull of the Moon and Sun on Earth's water": "",
  "Earthquakes on the ocean floor": "",
  "Tides are caused primarily by the gravitational attraction of the Moon and, to a lesser extent, the Sun on Earth's oceans. The Moon's gravity pulls ocean water toward it, creating a bulge of high tide on the side of Earth nearest the Moon.": "",
  "Spring tides occur when the Sun, Moon, and Earth are:": "",
  "During the spring season only": "",
  "At their greatest distance from each other": "",
  "Aligned in a straight line": "",
  "At right angles to each other": "",
  "Spring tides occur when the Sun, Moon, and Earth are aligned (during new moon and full moon phases). In this alignment, the gravitational forces of the Sun and Moon combine, producing the highest high tides and lowest low tides of the month.": "",
  "Neap tides produce:": "",
  "Only one high tide per day": "",
  "Tides with the smallest difference between high and low water": "",
  "The highest high tides and lowest low tides": "",
  "Tides that do not change for an entire month": "",
  "Neap tides occur during first and third quarter moon phases when the Sun and Moon are at right angles relative to Earth. Their gravitational pulls partially cancel each other out, resulting in the smallest tidal range with moderate high tides and moderate low tides.": "",
  "Most coastal areas experience how many high tides in a single day?": "",
  "Four": "",
  "Three": "",
  "Two": "",
  "One": "",
  "Most coastal locations experience a semidiurnal tidal pattern with two high tides and two low tides approximately every 24 hours and 50 minutes. This occurs because Earth rotates through two tidal bulges (one facing the Moon and one on the opposite side) each day.": "",
  "Which celestial body has the greatest influence on Earth's tides?": "",
  "The Sun": "",
  "Mars": "",
  "The Moon": "",
  "Jupiter": "",
  "Although the Sun is much more massive, the Moon has the greatest influence on Earth's tides because it is much closer to Earth. The tide-generating force depends strongly on distance, so the Moon's proximity makes its gravitational effect on tides about twice as strong as the Sun's.": "",
  "The Bay of Fundy in Canada is famous for having:": "",
  "No tides at all": "",
  "The most coral reefs in North America": "",
  "The highest tidal range in the world": "",
  "The coldest ocean water in the world": "",
  "The Bay of Fundy in eastern Canada holds the record for the world's highest tidal range, with water levels sometimes changing by more than 16 meters (53 feet) between high and low tide. Its funnel-shaped geography amplifies the tidal forces as water is funneled into an increasingly narrow bay.": "",
  "A tidal bulge forms on the side of Earth facing the Moon due to gravitational attraction. Why does a second tidal bulge form on the opposite side of Earth?": "",
  "Centrifugal force from the Earth-Moon system pushes water outward on the far side": "",
  "Ocean currents push water to the opposite side": "",
  "The Sun's gravity pulls water on the far side": "",
  "Warm water on the far side expands and rises": "",
  "The second tidal bulge on the side of Earth opposite the Moon is caused by inertia (centrifugal effect) from the Earth-Moon orbital system. On the far side, the Moon's gravitational pull is weakest, and the centrifugal force of the orbiting system pushes water outward, creating a second bulge.": "",
  "The tidal cycle shifts later by approximately how many minutes each day?": "",
  "10 minutes": "",
  "25 minutes": "",
  "90 minutes": "",
  "50 minutes": "",
  "The tidal cycle shifts approximately 50 minutes later each day because the Moon orbits Earth in the same direction as Earth's rotation. It takes Earth an extra 50 minutes beyond a 24-hour day to rotate to the same position relative to the advancing Moon.": "",
  "During which moon phases do spring tides occur?": "",
  "New moon and full moon": "",
  "Only during a full moon": "",
  "First quarter and third quarter": "",
  "Only during a waxing crescent": "",
  "Spring tides occur during both new moon and full moon phases because in both cases the Sun, Earth, and Moon are approximately aligned in a straight line. This alignment combines the gravitational forces of the Sun and Moon, producing extra-large tidal ranges.": "",
  "A 'flood tide' refers to:": "",
  "A catastrophic flood caused by a tsunami": "",
  "The period when the tide is falling and water moves away from shore": "",
  "An abnormally high tide caused by a hurricane": "",
  "The period when the tide is rising and water moves toward the shore": "",
  "A flood tide is the rising phase of the tide when water flows from the open ocean toward the shore, gradually increasing the water level along the coast. The opposite, when water recedes from shore, is called an ebb tide.": "",
  "What is a spring tide?": "",
  "A tide that only occurs during the spring season": "",
  "A tide caused by freshwater springs flowing into the ocean": "",
  "A tide with an extra-large tidal range that occurs when the Sun, Moon, and Earth are aligned": "",
  "A rapid rush of water into a narrow river channel": "",
  "A spring tide is a tide with an especially large tidal range (high high tides and low low tides) that occurs when the Sun, Moon, and Earth are aligned during new and full moon phases. The name 'spring' comes from the concept of water 'springing up,' not from the season.": "",
  "What is a neap tide?": "",
  "A tide with the smallest tidal range, occurring when the Sun and Moon are at right angles to Earth": "",
  "A tide that brings in large amounts of seaweed": "",
  "A tide that occurs only at night": "",
  "A tide that occurs only during winter months": "",
  "A neap tide occurs during the first and third quarter moon phases when the Sun and Moon are at right angles relative to Earth. Their gravitational forces partially counteract each other, resulting in the smallest difference between high and low tide levels.": "",
  "What does 'semidiurnal' mean in the context of tides?": "",
  "Having two high tides and two low tides of approximately equal height per day": "",
  "Having tides that occur only twice per month": "",
  "Having one high tide and one low tide per day": "",
  "Having no regular tidal pattern at all": "",
  "Semidiurnal tides feature two high tides and two low tides of roughly equal height in each tidal day (approximately 24 hours and 50 minutes). This is the most common tidal pattern, found along most of the Atlantic Ocean coastlines.": "",
  "What is a tidal range?": "",
  "The distance a tide travels horizontally up a beach": "",
  "The geographic area affected by tidal flooding": "",
  "The vertical difference in water height between high tide and low tide": "",
  "The time interval between two consecutive high tides": "",
  "The tidal range is the vertical difference in water level between high tide and low tide at a given location. Tidal ranges vary greatly around the world, from less than a meter in some areas to over 16 meters in the Bay of Fundy.": "",
  "What does 'ebb tide' mean?": "",
  "The rising of the tide during a full moon": "",
  "The highest point reached by a spring tide": "",
  "A tide that occurs during an eclipse": "",
  "The period when the tide is falling and water flows away from the shore": "",
  "An ebb tide is the receding or falling phase of the tide when water flows from the shore back toward the open ocean. It is the opposite of a flood tide, which is the incoming or rising phase of the tidal cycle.": "",
  "What is a diurnal tide?": "",
  "A tide that occurs only during the daytime": "",
  "A tide that has been disrupted by strong winds": "",
  "A tidal pattern with only one high tide and one low tide per tidal day": "",
  "A tide caused exclusively by the Sun's gravity": "",
  "A diurnal tide is a tidal pattern in which there is only one high tide and one low tide per tidal day. This pattern is less common than semidiurnal tides and is found in some parts of the Gulf of Mexico and Southeast Asia.": "",
  "What is a tidal bore?": "",
  "A wave that travels up a river or narrow bay as the incoming tide pushes against the outflowing current": "",
  "A device used to measure tidal height": "",
  "A channel drilled into the seafloor to study tides": "",
  "An extremely low tide that exposes the ocean floor": "",
  "A tidal bore is a wave that forms when an incoming high tide pushes into a shallow, narrowing river or bay against the outflowing current. The incoming tide is funneled into an increasingly confined space, creating a visible wave front that can travel upstream for miles.": "",
  "What does 'tidal current' mean?": "",
  "The vertical movement of water during a tsunami": "",
  "A permanent ocean current driven by wind patterns": "",
  "The horizontal flow of water caused by the rise and fall of the tides": "",
  "An electric current generated by tidal energy turbines": "",
  "A tidal current is the horizontal movement of water associated with the rising and falling of the tides. As the tide rises (flood current), water flows toward shore, and as the tide falls (ebb current), water flows away from shore.": "",
  "What is a mixed semidiurnal tide?": "",
  "A tide that alternates between spring and neap patterns each day": "",
  "A tide that only occurs in enclosed seas and bays": "",
  "A combination of wind-driven waves and gravitational tides": "",
  "A tidal pattern with two high tides and two low tides per day, but of unequal heights": "",
  "A mixed semidiurnal tide features two high tides and two low tides per day, but they have significantly different heights. One high tide is notably higher than the other, and one low tide is notably lower. This pattern is common along the Pacific coast of North America.": "",
  "What does 'tidal energy' refer to?": "",
  "Energy released by underwater earthquakes": "",
  "Renewable energy generated by harnessing the movement of tidal water": "",
  "The kinetic energy of waves created by surface winds": "",
  "Thermal energy stored in warm ocean surface water": "",
  "Tidal energy is a form of renewable energy that harnesses the kinetic and potential energy of tidal water movements to generate electricity. Tidal power plants use the predictable rise and fall of tides or the flow of tidal currents through turbines to produce clean energy.": "",
  "A family on vacation at the beach notices that the water has retreated much farther out than usual, exposing a wide stretch of sandy bottom. They check a lunar calendar and see it is a full moon. What type of tide are they most likely experiencing?": "",
  "A tidal bore": "",
  "A diurnal high tide": "",
  "A spring low tide": "",
  "A neap low tide": "",
  "During a full moon, the Sun, Earth, and Moon are aligned, producing spring tides with the greatest tidal range. The exceptionally low water level the family observes is the low tide phase of a spring tide, where water retreats much farther than during neap tide periods.": "",
  "A marine biology student observes that tide pool organisms along the coast are exposed to air for much shorter periods during one week compared to another. She checks the moon phase and finds it is a first quarter moon. What type of tide explains the shorter exposure time?": "",
  "Neap tides, because the low tide does not drop as far": "",
  "Spring tides, because the water stays high longer": "",
  "A tidal surge from an approaching storm": "",
  "Diurnal tides, because there is only one low tide per day": "",
  "During a first quarter moon, neap tides occur because the Sun and Moon are at right angles. Neap tides have a smaller tidal range, meaning low tide does not drop as far as during spring tides. This keeps tide pool organisms covered with water longer, reducing their air exposure time.": "",
  "A port engineer needs to schedule the passage of a large cargo ship through a shallow harbor channel. The ship requires at least 12 meters of water depth, but the channel is only 10 meters deep at mean sea level. When should the engineer schedule the ship's passage?": "",
  "During a neap low tide": "",
  "During an ebb tide": "",
  "During a spring high tide": "",
  "During a tidal bore": "",
  "Scheduling during a spring high tide ensures the maximum possible water depth in the channel. Spring tides produce the highest high tides, adding the most water above mean sea level, which would give the ship the extra depth it needs to safely transit the shallow channel.": "",
  "A fisherman on the Gulf Coast of Texas notices that his area only experiences one high tide and one low tide per day, unlike his friend on the Atlantic Coast of Florida who gets two of each. What type of tidal pattern does the Texas fisherman experience?": "",
  "Mixed semidiurnal": "",
  "Diurnal": "",
  "Neap": "",
  "Semidiurnal": "",
  "Parts of the Gulf Coast of Texas experience diurnal tides, meaning only one high tide and one low tide occur per tidal day. This contrasts with the semidiurnal pattern on much of the Atlantic Coast, where two high tides and two low tides occur daily.": "",
  "A coastal power company is considering building a tidal energy plant. They need a location with a very large tidal range to maximize electricity generation. Which of the following locations would be the BEST choice?": "",
  "A wide, open ocean beach with small tides": "",
  "A narrow, funnel-shaped bay with very large tidal ranges": "",
  "A sheltered lagoon with almost no tidal change": "",
  "A deep-water port with minimal tidal variation": "",
  "A narrow, funnel-shaped bay amplifies tidal ranges as the incoming water is compressed into a smaller space. Locations like the Bay of Fundy demonstrate that geography can dramatically increase tidal ranges, making such sites ideal for tidal energy generation.": "",
  "A scuba diver plans a dive near a rocky coast and wants to enter the water during slack tide for the calmest conditions. Slack tide occurs at the moment when:": "",
  "The Moon is at its closest approach to Earth": "",
  "The tidal current is at its strongest during spring tides": "",
  "The tide is neither rising nor falling, just before it reverses direction": "",
  "Waves are at their largest due to storm activity": "",
  "Slack tide (or slack water) is the brief period when the tidal current changes direction, and there is little to no horizontal water movement. It occurs at the transition between flood tide and ebb tide, making it the calmest time for divers to enter the water near shorelines.": "",
  "A group of clam diggers arrives at a beach on the Pacific coast. They notice that this morning's low tide is much lower than this afternoon's low tide. Which tidal pattern best describes this observation?": "",
  "Diurnal tides": "",
  "Semidiurnal tides": "",
  "Neap tides": "",
  "Mixed semidiurnal tides": "",
  "Mixed semidiurnal tides feature two high tides and two low tides per day, but with noticeably different heights. One low tide is significantly lower than the other, which explains why the morning low was much lower than the afternoon low. This pattern is common along the Pacific coast of North America.": "",
  "During a documentary, a narrator explains that the Moon is slowly moving farther from Earth over millions of years. If the Moon were significantly farther away, how would this affect Earth's tides?": "",
  "Tides would become weaker because the Moon's gravitational pull would decrease": "",
  "Tides would stop completely and the oceans would be perfectly flat": "",
  "Tides would become much larger and more extreme": "",
  "Tides would become unpredictable and random": "",
  "Tidal forces decrease rapidly with distance (inversely proportional to the cube of the distance). If the Moon were significantly farther away, its gravitational pull on Earth's oceans would be weaker, resulting in smaller tidal bulges and a reduced tidal range.": "",
  "A coastal homeowner notices that high tide reached their property line during a full moon in January, but during a full moon in July, the high tide was even higher and flooded their yard. What additional factor likely contributed to the extra-high July tide?": "",
  "July has warmer water which naturally rises higher on the beach": "",
  "The Sun was in a different constellation during July": "",
  "The Moon was closer to Earth (near perigee) during the July full moon, increasing its gravitational pull": "",
  "Strong offshore winds in July pushed water higher onto shore": "",
  "When a full moon coincides with the Moon being at or near perigee (its closest approach to Earth), the resulting tide is called a perigean spring tide or 'king tide.' The closer proximity of the Moon amplifies its gravitational pull, producing even higher high tides than a normal spring tide.": "",
  "A kayaker is planning to paddle through a narrow inlet between two islands. Locals warn that the tidal currents through the inlet can exceed 8 knots during certain times. When would the tidal current through this inlet be the STRONGEST?": "",
  "During the exact moment of high tide": "",
  "During slack tide at a spring tide cycle": "",
  "During slack tide at a neap tide cycle": "",
  "During the mid-point of a flood or ebb phase of a spring tide": "",
  "Tidal currents are strongest during the middle of the flood or ebb phase, when water is moving most rapidly between high and low tide levels. During spring tides, the larger tidal range means more water must flow through the narrow inlet in the same time period, producing the fastest and most powerful tidal currents.": ""
}